Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by the Uruguay's President Jose Mujica and comprising several ministers and entrepreneur starts on Tuesday her visit by Mexico to expand trade between the two countries and to discuss political issues in the region
Mujica meets next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón. It will be according to the Uruguay president of the peak of his full schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the group of Uruguayer living in Mexico.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara is "for the exchange of information on all areas between the two countries," the president of the South American country announced on his website.
According to local media Mujica seek support Calderón's regarding the incident with France, when the French leader Nicolas Sarkozy set at the summit of the G20 in the French city of Cannes, the South American country on a list of tax havens.
In his discourse Sarkozy with those countries which are still as tax havens to exclude from the international community. This declaration was rejected by Uruguay and prompted threatened a question during his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has since November, the presidency of the G20, a group consisting of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world. Since January this year, there is an agreement on the exchange of tax information on the avoidance of double orientation with the South American country.
The government of Uruguay has tried in recent years to speed up the realisation of agreements on the exchange of tax information to be from the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) deleted, countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
On a commercial level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay, which has contributed to a growing freight exchanges between the two countries since 2004.
